import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    source_counts = data['source'].value_counts()
    target_counts = data['target'].value_counts()

    fig, ax1 = plt.subplots()
    ax2 = ax1.twinx()

    ax1.bar(source_counts.index, source_counts.values, color='b', alpha=0.5, label='Source')
    ax2.bar(target_counts.index, target_counts.values, color='g', alpha=0.5, label='Target')

    ax1.set_xlabel('Categories')
    ax1.set_ylabel('Source Frequency')
    ax2.set_ylabel('Target Frequency')

    plt.title('What is the distribution of source and target in the dataset?', wrap=True)
    fig.legend(loc='upper right')

    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    # Create a pivot table with source as rows, target as columns, and count of occurrences as values
    pivot_table = data.pivot_table(index='source', columns='target', aggfunc='size', fill_value=0)

    # Create a heatmap using seaborn
    sns.heatmap(pivot_table, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='viridis')

    # Set the title and add a legend
    plt.title('What is the most common source and target combination in the dataset?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend(title='Count', loc='upper right')

    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    # Group by source and count the number of targets
    grouped_data = data.groupby('source')['target'].count().reset_index()
    
    # Calculate the average number of targets per source
    avg_targets = grouped_data['target'].mean()
    
    # Create a bar chart of the average number of targets per source
    ax = grouped_data.plot.bar(x='source', y='target', legend=False)
    
    # Add a horizontal line representing the average number of targets
    plt.axhline(y=avg_targets, color='r', linestyle='--', label=f'Average: {avg_targets:.2f}')
    
    # Set the chart title and legend
    plt.title('What is the average number of targets per source in the dataset?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    
    # Rotate x-axis labels for better readability
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    unique_sources = data['source'].nunique()
    unique_targets = data['target'].nunique()
    proportions = [unique_sources, unique_targets]
    labels = ['Unique Sources', 'Unique Targets']
    colors = ['blue', 'orange']

    plt.pie(proportions, labels=labels, colors=colors, autopct='%.2f%%')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of unique sources and targets in the dataset?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend(labels, loc='upper right')
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
